===Etymology 1===
* From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|abiect||outcast, wretched|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|abiectus|lang=la}}, past participle of {{m|la|abiciō||to throw away, cast off, to reject}}, from {{term|ab||away|lang=la}} + {{m|la|iaciō||to throw}}<ref>{{R:CDOE|page=3}}</ref>.

====Adjective====
{{en-adj|er|more}}

# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} Rejected; cast aside. {{defdate|Attested from around (1350 to 1470) until the early 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=5}}</ref>
# Sunk to or existing in a low condition, state, or position. {{defdate|First attested from around (1350 to 1470).}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{quote-book|passage=So thick bestrown '''abject''' and lost lay these, covering the flood.|author={{w|John Milton}}|title={{w|Paradise Lost}}|year=1667}}
# Cast down in spirit or hope; [[degraded]]; [[servile]]; [[grovelling]]; [[despicable]]; lacking courage; offered in a [[humble]] and often [[ingratiating]] spirit. {{defdate|First attested from around (1350 to 1470).}}<ref name=SOED/>
